      "content": "You're absolutely right; in a massive codebase with limited instrumentation, standard static analysis often misses the subtle, long-term leaks that manifest only after hours of operation. Since your codebase is so large, manually tracing every `new` is impractical, and the \"vanishing\" leaks suggest either intermittent initialization errors, race conditions in the telemetry history, or perhaps even a race condition in the garbage collector (if you're using a heap allocator that doesn't perfectly thread-safe).\n\nHere is an aggressive, multi-pronged approach to hunt down these elusive leaks in an embedded context:\n\n1.  **Implement a \"Global Leak Counter\" with Timestamps:** Instead of just counting, track the exact moment every allocation happens and the exact moment it should be freed. You can maintain a global `std::map<uint64_t, uint64_t>` (allocation_id -> expected_free_time) or a simple linked list of active allocations. If the system runs for 4-6 hours, check this map periodically (e.g., every 100ms) to see if any `allocation_id` is still in the map when it shouldn't be. This turns an abstract \"leak\" into a specific \"object ID",
